{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"466c866f-164e-4afb-8431-9dd7bc607f27","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there's no request pipeline — the DI scope lives for the **entire app lifetime**. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning you get the same `DbContext` instance across all page navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new `DbContext` per injection (simplest fix).\n\n2. **Use a factory** — inject `IDbContextFactory<MyContext>` and create/dispose contexts manually:\n   ```csharp\n   services.AddDbContextFactory<MyContext>(opts => ...);\n   ```\n   Then in your view model:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\n3. **Create manual scopes** — inject `IServiceScopeFactory` and create short-lived scopes yourself.\n\nOption 2 (factory) is generally recommended as it gives you explicit lifetime control and avoids issues with tracked entities accumulating in memory.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80943dae-b9f4-47a4-bbb9-488b3822aa0f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, \"scoped\" means per-HTTP-request. In MAUI, there's no HTTP request pipeline, so \"scoped\" effectively behaves like a singleton — the scope never ends during the app's lifetime. That's why the DbContext persists across navigations.","outputTokens":387,"requestId":"0822:114A89:A88B93:C36179:69F2AA4D"},"id":"af28ca6e-1776-4212-aa38-55d72160c157","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:03:19.921Z","parentId":"ecb2af01-bdba-4e35-9ec0-fd2f0571de0a"}
